MEDIUM|internal/debate/cluster.go:74|filterMergedClusters resolves a gray-zone radar item to its cluster ID through indexClusters, which keys on {File, Line, clusterDisplayProblem} (longest member problem) with last-write-wins. Two DISTINCT clusters sharing the same canonical File+Line AND the same longest-member problem text collapse to one map entry, so an item can resolve to the wrong cluster's ID — re-suppressing a non-merged co-located cluster (the residual of the original over-suppression bug) or re-debating a merged one. Non-corrupting and self-healing on the next fresh reconcile, and narrow (requires identical longest-problem across distinct clusters), but it leaves a thin gap in the AC4 promise. The headline AC4 test only covers the case where the two clusters have DIFFERENT longest problems.|Make indexClusters value a slice (map[FindingKey][]AmbiguousCluster) and have filterMergedClusters suppress an item only when SOME cluster at that key carries a merged ID, or key the radar item to its cluster by the stable AmbiguousCluster.ID rather than File+Line+longestProblem. Add a test with two distinct clusters sharing File+Line+longest-problem asserting the non-merged one survives.|correctness|120|internal/debate/cluster.go:35-41,72-79|claude
LOW|internal/debate/cluster.go:74|The merged-ID lookup mergedIDs[c.ID] is safe only by accident: the producer loop at line 64 guards f.ClusterID != "" so the set can never contain the empty string, but the consumer does not defend itself. A future refactor that admitted a blank key upstream would suppress every empty-ID cluster at once.|Make the consumer self-protecting: add c.ID != "" to the condition at line 74 so suppression never depends on the producer-side guard. Verify with a test feeding a cluster with ID:"" against a mergedIDs set containing "".|error-handling|15|internal/debate/cluster.go:62-79|claude
LOW|internal/debate/cluster.go:214|applyOneClusterMerge stamps merged.ClusterID = c.ID unconditionally. AmbiguousID is a non-empty sha256 hex for any dedupe-created cluster, so this is unreachable from current code — but a hand-edited ambiguous.json or a future producer that omits the ID writes a survivor with ClusterMerged:true and ClusterID:"". filterMergedClusters treats that as a legacy record and suppresses nothing, so the cluster is re-debated every run and never self-heals (re-stamping just rewrites an empty ID), contradicting the self-heal comment at cluster.go:56-58.|Only set ClusterMerged/ClusterID when c.ID != "", or log a WARN when merging a cluster with no ID so the broken-idempotency case is observable. Add a test merging a cluster with ID:"".|error-handling|30|internal/debate/cluster.go:209-214|claude
LOW|internal/debate/cluster.go:21|clusterDisplayProblem duplicates reconcile.longestProblem (longest PROBLEM among members, strict-greater-than tie-break keeping the first). Idempotency correctness depends on the two staying identical forever: grayZoneItem sets it.Problem via longestProblem, indexClusters keys via clusterDisplayProblem, and the lookup matches only if they agree. The coupling is pinned by TestIndexClusters_RoundTripsBuildDisagreementsProblem but lives as two separate impls across packages.|Collapse to one exported helper in reconcile (e.g. reconcile.ClusterDisplayProblem) called by both grayZoneItem and indexClusters, eliminating the drift surface. Verify existing debate idempotency tests still pass.|maintainability|30|internal/debate/cluster.go:18-29|claude
LOW|internal/debate/cluster.go:71|filterMergedClusters allocates a full-capacity out slice and copies every item whenever at least one merged ID exists, even though the typical re-run suppresses 0-1 of N items. The early return at line 68 only covers the no-merged-records case.|Track whether any item was actually skipped and return the original items slice unchanged when none was (scan-first, copy-only-if-needed). Minor; only worth it for large radars. Existing tests pin behavior.|performance|15|internal/debate/cluster.go:67-80|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/emit.go:66|The JSONFinding type doc comment still describes it as the AC 01-06 schema mentioning only the reserved Verification field. It was not updated as Epics 5.0/5.4/6.0/6.1/6.2 each appended an omitempty field (path_valid, path_warning, path_suggestion, cluster_merged, cluster_id), so the header materially understates the current schema.|Add one line to the type doc noting the schema is additively extended by later epics (path-validation 5.x, cross-exam 6.x) and that all such fields are omitempty for backward byte-compatibility.|maintainability|15|internal/reconcile/emit.go:66-83|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/emit.go:110|The ClusterID field comment asserts cross-package behavior (stamped by the cross-examination apply path; read by the debate radar) with no file:line cross-reference, unlike the Verification comment which cites emit.go:145. If applyOneClusterMerge/filterMergedClusters are renamed or moved, this comment rots silently with no compiler or test linkage.|Add a // see internal/debate/cluster.go (applyOneClusterMerge / filterMergedClusters) cross-reference to the ClusterID comment.|maintainability|5|internal/reconcile/emit.go:110-118|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/emit.go:122|No test pins the negative invariant that JSONFindings()/RenderJSON never emit cluster_id or cluster_merged. The AC1 byte-identity guarantee currently rests only on the Merged struct lacking those fields; a future maintainer who adds ClusterID to Merged and wires it into JSONFindings would silently break AC1 and no reconcile-package test would fail (existing tests only marshal a hand-built JSONFinding).|Add a test that builds a Result with findings and asserts RenderJSON/JSONFindings output contains neither cluster_id nor cluster_merged, locking the reconcile-path-never-stamps contract.|testing|30|internal/reconcile/emit_test.go:371-393|claude

